<b> Castle History: Brizai  </b> <br> Birzai Castle, commissioned by Duke Kristupas Radvila, served to defend <br> the northern border of Lithuania. Its construction began in 1586, <br> and it became the main seat of the Birzai-Dubingiai Radziwiłł  <br> family. During the wars with Sweden, it was a crucial defensive structure. <br> However, it was heavily damaged and destroyed by the Swedes in the 17th <br> century. Despite attempts to rebuild it, it was once again taken by the Swedes <br> and ultimately destroyed. In the 1980s, the castle was restored in the <br> Renaissance-Baroque style and now houses a library and a regional history <br> museum called 'Sėla'. It also serves as the Birzai Regional Museum, <br> offering educational programs for visitors.
<br><b> What's Nearby </b> <br> Eko basų kojų parkas (Barefoot Walking Trail) - 11 Minute Drive (3.8 Miles) <br> Kirkilų pramogų parkas (Amusement Park) - 11 Minute Drive (4.6 Miles) <br> Senovines Technikos Muziejus (Museum) - 15 Minute Drive (8.0 Miles) <br> Vynuogynas "Šiaurės uoga" (Vinyard) - 12 Minute Drive (5.7 Miles)  <br><br>
